Abstract = {{Timeliness, coherence, and correctness of information and data flow
   between the shop floor and the upper level planning systems in an
   enterprise is critical to the decision making in response to internal
   and external conditions. How much each decision contributes to the value
   an enterprise generates depends on the quality of the information flow
   among the various levels within the enterprise.
   Uncertainties in manufacturing environment due to internal and external
   disturbances necessitates that shop floor control is dynamic in nature.
   Data collected through shop floor control systems have to be passed in
   an appropriate format to other production planning and control modules
   in real time. Providing a seamless flow of information will complement
   the upper level enterprise resource planning (ERP) modules by providing
   data with minimum latency. In this way, planned orders will be scheduled
   effectively along with backlog orders based on the real-time status of
   the manufacturing equipment, the amount of inventory will be known at
   all times, and the quality control problems will be reported in
   real-time to avoid further problems. From the standpoint of supply chain
   management, the impact of providing real time data on events and
   decisions at any level is much critical owing to the involvement of
   several enterprises, wherein their business processes are highly
   integrated. At this level, real time data helps in such as knowing the
   status of a particular customer order, providing accurate delivery time
   of orders, and making robust preventive plant maintenance plans.
   This paper is focused on the information flow gap between the production
   environment and upper level enterprise resource management levels, with
   emphasis on master planning, which acts as a link between the
   manufacturing systems, suppliers and market. Information flow is
   analyzed from two perspectives: (1) Within the organization, and (2)
   Across the supply chain. Various manufacturing environments are compared
